---
const criteria = [
  {
    label: "Uniform fraction",
    detail:
      "At least 80% of per-question model_distribution entries are within 0.01 of perfectly uniform (e.g. {0.25, 0.25, 0.25, 0.25} for a 4-option question).",
  },
  {
    label: "Negligible refusals",
    detail:
      "Mean per-question model_refusal_rate ≤ 0.05. A model that genuinely refuses most questions is a legitimate safety pattern, not a failed API response.",
  },
  {
    label: "Enough questions",
    detail:
      "At least 10 questions in the run. Shorter runs don't give enough signal to distinguish real flat distributions from API-failure garbage.",
  },
];
---

<section class="w-full max-w-4xl mx-auto py-12" id="run-validity">
  <h2
    class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-text dark:text-text-dark mb-2"
  >
    Run Validity Filtering
  </h2>
  <p class="text-muted mb-6 max-w-2xl">
    Silent API failures — budget exhaustion, missed model aliases, provider
    fallbacks — can return responses that parse cleanly but carry no real
    signal, producing a run whose per-question distributions are all
    perfectly uniform. Existing parse-failure tracking does not catch this
    case because the response <em>did</em> parse. We filter these runs at
    publish time so they never reach the leaderboard.
  </p>

  <p class="text-muted mb-6 max-w-2xl">
    A run is excluded when <strong>all three</strong> of the following hold:
  </p>

  <ul class="space-y-3 mb-6">
    {
      criteria.map((c) => (
        <li class="flex gap-3">
          <span class="text-primary dark:text-primary-light mt-1 shrink-0">
            &bull;
          </span>
          <span class="text-sm text-muted">
            <strong class="text-text dark:text-text-dark">{c.label}.</strong>{" "}
            {c.detail}
          </span>
        </li>
      ))
    }
  </ul>

  <p class="text-muted max-w-2xl text-sm">
    Excluded runs are listed in <code
      class="text-xs bg-muted/10 rounded px-1.5 py-0.5"
      >leaderboard.json#excluded_runs</code
    > for transparency, and operators can run
    <code class="text-xs bg-muted/10 rounded px-1.5 py-0.5"
      >synthbench scan-invalid</code
    > locally against any results directory. The rule is deliberately strict:
    we would rather miss a borderline case than false-flag a legitimate run
    whose distributions happen to be flat.
  </p>
</section>
